   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Iowa_0001_1844-12_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <note>MSL E23 1844</note>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworths Town</placeName>
                  <lb/>
                  <date when="1844-12-18">Dec<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. 18<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1844<lb/>
                  </date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>
                  Dear Sir<lb/>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               I am truly obliged by your<lb/>
               taking the trouble to write to<lb/>
               me on my business in the midst<lb/>
               of all your own pressure of<lb/>
               business -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I have written again to<lb/>
                  my bankers Mess<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Hoare to<lb/>
               request them to make fresh<lb/>
               search as I have a rec<hi rend="superscript">t</hi> from<lb/>
                  them dated Dec - 33 for a <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Liverpool_ENK">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Liver<lb/>
                     pool</orig>
                     <reg>Liverpool</reg>
                  </choice>
               </placeName> &amp; <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Manchester_ENK">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Man<hi rend="superscript">c</hi>.</orig>
                     <reg>Manchester</reg>
                  </choice>
               </placeName> share - Till I <choice>
                  <orig>re<lb/>
                     eive</orig>
                  <reg>receive</reg>
               </choice>
               Mess<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Hoares reply I will<lb/>
               not trouble you to send me a form<lb/>
               of affidavit of the loss of the <unclear>Scrip</unclear>
               <lb/>
               - But so soon as I am assured of the<lb/>
               loss I will write again to you -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>In the mean time I should<lb/>
               be glad to sell the Â£40 new share<lb/>
               which you mention to me; I was<lb/>
               aware that I possessed it; but I<lb/>
               did not purpose transferring it<lb/>
               with the whole share to M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
               <lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Iowa_0001_1844-12_page02.jpg"/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF1">Francis Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I do wish to sell it - since it<lb/>
               is saleable as you tell me for<lb/>
               about Â£34 -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Be the same more or less <del>I <choice>
                     <orig>sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>.</orig>
                     <reg>should</reg>
                  </choice>
               </del>
               <lb/>
               within a few shillings or so<lb/>
               I request you will have the<lb/>
               goodness to sell it for me<lb/>
               and either pay the proceeds to<lb/>
               my account at Hoares Bank,<lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#37-Fleet-Street_ENK">Fleet Street London</placeName> or send<lb/>
               it to me by post in half Bank<lb/>
               note - or notes.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I suppose it is not necessary to<lb/>
               produce any scrip for this <choice>
                  <orig>pur-<lb/>
                  pose</orig>
                  <reg>purpose</reg>
               </choice> - I dont believe that I ever<lb/>
               had any -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Will you be so kind to <choice>
                  <orig>remem<lb/>
                  -ber</orig>
                  <reg>remember</reg>
               </choice> me in the kindest manner<lb/>
                  to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LawrX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Lawrence</persName>. I have now<lb/>
               recovered from illness sufficiently<lb/>
               to be allowed to come down to<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Iowa_0001_1844-12_page03.jpg"/>
               <hi rend="underline">the Library</hi> our common sitting<lb/>
               room &amp; I have been permitted<lb/>
               the use of pen and ink. But<lb/>
               I am charged to be abstemious<lb/>
               in their use<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I cannot however refrain<lb/>
               from mentioning to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LawrX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Lawrence</persName>
               <lb/>
               that we have been much pleased<lb/>
               by a novel we have just read<lb/>
                  which <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BentR1">Bentley</persName> sent to me to<lb/>
               learn my opinion of<lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Const1">"Constancy &amp; Contrition"</title> 2 stories<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I like Contrition much<lb/>
               the best and think it shows<lb/>
               great power - real genius<lb/>
               - and could have been written<lb/>
               only by a really good person<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>The good characters being<lb/>
               so truly amiable generous &amp;<lb/>
               engaging - not at all <hi rend="underline">stupid</hi>
               <lb/>
               good people - I am told that<lb/>
               this book is written by a very<lb/>
               young <del>Lady</del> Miss <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GoodX1">Goodrick</persName> of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Beaufort_Cheltenham_ENK">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Beau-<lb/>
               fort</orig>
                     <reg>Beaufort</reg>
                  </choice> House</placeName>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Cheltenham_ENK">Cheltenham</placeName> - Does <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LawrX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. L</persName>
               <lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Iowa_0001_1844-12_page04.jpg"/>
               know any thing about her? I Pray tell me. I am go<lb/>
               to write to her as I can do so<lb/>
               with pleasure having heartfelt<lb/>
               praise to offer - I never <hi rend="underline">can</hi>
               <lb/>
               give or offer any other - Indeed<lb/>
               I think those who give <hi rend="underline">insincere</hi>
               <lb/>
               or false praise knowing it to be<lb/>
               false debase their own coin<lb/>
               and make their praise of no value<lb/>
               and render themselves of<lb/>
               worse than no value - <choice>
                  <orig>con-<lb/>
                  temptible</orig>
                  <reg>contemptible</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>You will perceive that<lb/>
               these 2 last pages <unclear>on</unclear> are not for<lb/>
                  your reading but for <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LawrX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Lawrence</persName>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Excuse my Novellist habits<lb/>
               and believe me Dear Sir<lb/>
               nevertheless a woman of business<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               &amp; very truly<lb/>
               Your obliged <choice>
                  <orig>Ser<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>.</orig>
                  <reg>Servant</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
         </div>
      </body>
